25|$|<b>Formal</b> <b>logic</b> is {{the study}} of {{inference}} with purely formal content. An inference possesses a purely formal content if it can be expressed as a particular application of a wholly abstract rule, that is, a rule that is not about any particular thing or property. The works of Aristotle contain the earliest known formal study of logic. Modern <b>formal</b> <b>logic</b> follows and expands on Aristotle. In many definitions of logic, logical inference and inference with purely formal content are the same. This does not render the notion of informal logic vacuous, because no <b>formal</b> <b>logic</b> captures all of the nuances of natural language.|$|E
