50|$|Type {{theory is}} closely related to (and in some cases {{overlaps}} with) type systems, which are a programming language feature used to reduce bugs. Type theory was created to avoid paradoxes in a variety of <b>formal</b> <b>logics</b> and rewrite systems.|$|R
5000|$|Semantics (from [...] sēmantikos, [...] "significant") is the {{linguistic}} and philosophical study of meaning, in language, programming languages, <b>formal</b> <b>logics,</b> and semiotics. It {{is concerned with}} the relationship between signifiers—like words, phrases, signs, and symbols—and what they stand for, their denotation.|$|R
25|$|The {{foundational}} {{philosophy of}} formalism, {{as exemplified by}} David Hilbert, {{is a response to}} the paradoxes of set theory, and is based on <b>formal</b> <b>logic.</b> Virtually all mathematical theorems today can be formulated as theorems of set theory. The truth of a mathematical statement, in this view, is represented {{by the fact that the}} statement can be derived from the axioms of set theory using the rules of <b>formal</b> <b>logic.</b>|$|E
25|$|The <b>formal</b> <b>logic</b> {{that emerged}} {{early in the}} 20th century also requires, at minimum, unary {{negation}} and quantified variables ranging over some universe of discourse.|$|E
